file.string: You are walking down the street, and you see a homeless person sitting on the sidewalk. They are dirty and dishevelled, and they are begging for money. What do you do?
You start to cry and scream for help
You try to calm down and assess the situation. You look for clues in the room that might tell you what happened.
You try to open the door, but it is locked. You start to feel claustrophobic and panic again.
You sit back in the bed and wait for someone to come in.

You are at a job interview, and the interviewer asks you the following question: Interviewer: Tell me about a time when you had to deal with a difficult coworker. How did you handle the situation?
I avoided the coworker as much as possible
I confronted the coworker directly and tried to resolve the issue.
I went to my manager for help
I did nothing and hoped that the problem would go away on its own.
You are in a relationship with someone who has been cheating on you. You find out about the affair and confront your partner. They admit to cheating and say that they are sorry. What do you do?
You forgive your partner and give them another chance.
You break up with your partner immediately.
You take some time to think about what you want to do.
You stay with your partner but keep a close eye on them to make sure they don\'t cheat again.
You are driving home from work, and you see a car accident. There are people injured in the accident. What do you do?
You stop and offer to help the injured people.
You keep driving and call 911.
You slow down and look at the accident, but you don\'t stop.
You drive by the accident as quickly as possible.
You are at a party, and you see someone who is being bullied. What do you do?
You ignore the situation and walk away.
You intervene and try to stop the bullying.
You go to a trusted adult and tell them what is happening.
You do nothing because you\'re afraid of getting involved.
You are at work, and you are feeling overwhelmed. You have too much to do and you don\'t know how you are going to get everything done. What do you do?
You start to panic and feel like you are going to have a breakdown.
You take a step back and assess the situation. You break down the tasks into smaller steps and prioritize them.
You ask for help from your coworkers or manager.
You keep working until you finish everything, even if it means sacrificing your sleep and health.
You are in a relationship with someone who is controlling and manipulative. They try to isolate you from your friends and family, and they make you feel bad about yourself. What do you do?
You stay in the relationship because you are afraid of what your partner will do if you leave
You break up with your partner and get support from your friends and family.
You talk to a therapist about what you are going through.
You try to change your partner\'s behaviour.
You are at a funeral, and you see someone who is crying uncontrollably. What do you do?
You give them a hug and offer your condolences.
You leave them alone to grieve in their own way.
You tell them that they should be strong and that their loved one would want them to be happy.
You tell them that you understand how they feel and that you\'re there for them if they need anything.
You are at a job interview, and you are asked to talk about your biggest weakness. What do you say?
You say that you are perfect and have no weaknesses.
You say that you are a hard worker and that you are always willing to learn new things.
You say that you are a perfectionist and that you sometimes have difficulty delegating tasks.
You say that you are afraid of public speaking and that you are working on overcoming this fear.
You are walking down the street, and you see someone who is clearly lost. What do you do?
You ignore them and walk by.
You ask them if they need help.
You offer to walk them to their destination.
You call the police and report them as a lost person.
You try to cheer them up and encourage them to do things they enjoy.
You lend a listening ear and let them know that you are there for them.
You try to figure out what is causing their depression and fix the problem.
You suggest that they seek professional help.
You are in a relationship with someone who is depressed. They are withdrawn and uninterested in activities that they used to enjoy. What do you do?
You are at work, and you overhear your coworkers talking about you behind your back. They are saying negative things about you and your work. What do you do?
You confront your coworkers and tell them to stop talking about you behind your back.
You ignore your coworkers and try to focus on your work.
You talk to your manager about what happened.
You start to doubt yourself and wonder if your coworkers are right about you.
You are at a social event, and you feel anxious and uncomfortable. You start to sweat and your heart races. What do you do?
You excuse yourself and go to the bathroom to calm down.
You try to find a quiet place where you can sit and relax.
You talk to a trusted friend or family member about how you are feeling.
You try to force yourself to relax and enjoy yourself, even though you don\'t feel like it.
You are giving a presentation at work, and you suddenly forget what you are supposed to say. You start to feel panicky and your heart races. What do you do?
You take a deep breath and start over.
You apologize to the audience and say that you need a moment to collect your thoughts.
You try to wing it and hope that no one notices that you have forgotten what you are supposed to say.
You run out of the room and have a panic attack.
You are in a relationship with someone who is constantly criticizing you and putting you down. What do you do?
You try to ignore their criticism and focus on the positive aspects of the relationship.
You talk to your partner about how their criticism is making you feel.
You set boundaries and let your partner know that their criticism is unacceptable.
You leave the relationship.
